  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the word of God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] How Shemaiah and other prophets received their commission is not always explained. Sometimes it is said ‘the Lord sent’ (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 12:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 12:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The prompting by a vision in sleep is most frequently recorded, and this we may assume in other cases to have been the way in which God’s message came.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Shemaiah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Beside the present notice of him, Shemaiah is also mentioned at the time when Shishak, king of Egypt, invaded Judæa and besieged Jerusalem (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). He then was sent with a message of comfort to the princes of Judah. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he is said to have written a chronicle of the reign of Rehoboam.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 22.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "But the word of God came unto Shemaiah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [This part of the history is probably derived from the \"book\" which this prophet wrote (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). When Keil describes him as \"a prophet who is not mentioned again,\" he has surely overlooked ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:7, 8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where we find him prophesying with reference to the army of Shishak], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the man of God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [a common expression in the books of Kings. It rarely occurs in the other Scriptures. This designation is not altogether synonymous with \"prophet.\" It is used, for example, of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "angels",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 13:6, 8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Moses",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 33:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "David",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 8:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and would embrace ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "any",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " minister or servant of God, while ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "נָבִיא",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is restricted to the teaching order. There were ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "false",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " prophets, but no false men of God. It is also worth considering whether the name of prophet may not have been practically restricted to, or bestowed by preference on, those who had received a prophetic training, the \"sons of the prophets\" who had been taught in the schools. Cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 10:5-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 19:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 7:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "saying",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". 1 Kings 12:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But after the return of Rehoboam to Jerusalem he was still desirous of bringing back the seceders by force of arms, and raised for that purpose an army of 180,000 men out of all Judah, the tribe of Benjamin, and the rest of the people, i.e., the Israelites dwelling in the cities of Judah, - a number which does not appear too large according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 24:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But the prophet Shemaiah, a prophet who is not mentioned again, received instructions from God to forbid the king to go to war with their brethren the Israelites, \"for this thing was from the Lord.\" הזּה הדּבר, \"this thing, i.e., his being deprived of the sovereignty over ten tribes, but not their rebellion\" (Seb. Schmidt). For the fact itself, see the remark on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 12:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The king and the people hearkened to this word. ללכת ישׁוּבוּ, \"they turned to go,\" i.e., they gave up the intended expedition and returned home. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 11:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " we have the explanatory phrase מלּכת ישׁוּבוּ. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]